       <li>
        <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/25/spitting-at-science-the-unjustified-criminalization-of-spitting-while-hiv-positive/">
         <img src="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/water-1132215-e1551116161761.jpg?fit=1646%2C950&amp;resize=1920%2C550"/>
         <div class="flex-caption">
          <h2 class="entry-title">
           Spitting at Science: The Unjustified Criminalization of Spitting While HIV-Positive
          </h2>
          <div class="excerpt">
           Saliva doesn’t transmit HIV, yet a number of states explicitly criminalize the act of spitting if one is HIV-positive. These laws are grossly out of step with our current medical and social understanding of HIV.
          </div>
         </div>
        </a>
       </li>
      </ul>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div class="container main-content-area">
     <div class="row side-pull-left">
      <div class="main-content-inner col-sm-12 col-md-8">
       <div class="content-area" id="primary">
        <main class="site-main" id="main" role="main">
         <article class="post-27328 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-genetics-in-medicine category-health-law-policy" id="post-27328">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/" title="Precision Medicine’s Impact on the Doctor-Patient Relationship">
            <img alt="" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27358" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"4.5","credit":"Getty Images\/iStockphoto","camera":"X-T10","caption":"Doctors and patients sit and talk. At the table near the window in the hospital.","created_timestamp":"1504104682","copyright":"This content is subject to copyright.","focal_length":"39","iso":"200","shutter_speed":"0.005","title":"Doctors and patients sit and talk. At the table near the window in the hospital.","orientation":"1"}' data-image-title="Doctors and patients sit and talk. At the table near the window in the hospital." data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?fit=648%2C432" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?fit=2121%2C1414" data-orig-size="2121,1414" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/doctors-and-patients-sit-and-talk-at-the-table-near-the-window-in-the-hospital-2/" height="410" src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/doctor_patient_care.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750">
            </img>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/" rel="bookmark">
               Precision Medicine’s Impact on the Doctor-Patient Relationship
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-08T16:14:58+00:00">
                 March 8, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-08T16:14:58+00:00">
                 March 8, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/kmurphy/">
                 Genetics in Medicine
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              <strong>
               By Paul S. Appelbaum and Lawand Gil Eyal
              </strong>
             </p>
             <p>
              Healthcare is now entering a much-anticipated era of “precision medicine” (PM), an effort characterized
              <a href="https://allofus.nih.gov/">
               “[b]y taking into account individual differences in lifestyle, environment, and biology” to “accelerate research and improve health”
              </a>
              .
             </p>
             <p>
              The extent to which these goals are achievable and generalizable has been extensively debated, but often lost in the discussion is the likely impact of PM on the doctor-patient relationship, still the primary means of delivering medical care. As we and our colleagues noted in our recent commentary in
              <a href="https://rdcu.be/bpzel">
               <em>
                Genetics in Medicine
               </em>
              </a>
              , multiple changes are looming in both the doctor’s and the patient’s roles. Here we highlight just two of them: the proliferation of uncertainty and its downloading to the patient; and the diminution in the control and authority of the physician.
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/08/precision-medicines-impact-on-the-doctor-patient-relationship/#more-27328">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27338 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-fda category-featured category-health-law-policy" id="post-27338">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-resigns-twitter-reactions/" title="FDA Commissioner Gottlieb Resigns: Twitter Reactions">
            <img alt="FDA scott gottlieb" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27034" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"1"}' data-image-title="shutterstock_751933786" data-large-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?fit=648%2C413" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?zoom=3&amp;resize=750%2C410 2250w" data-medium-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?fit=300%2C191" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?fit=3000%2C1910" data-orig-size="3000,1910" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2018/11/29/how-scott-gottlieb-is-wrong-on-the-gene-edited-baby-debacle/shutterstock_751933786/" height="410" src="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_751933786.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750">
            </img>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-resigns-twitter-reactions/" rel="bookmark">
               FDA Commissioner Gottlieb Resigns: Twitter Reactions
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-resigns-twitter-reactions/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-07T13:05:23+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-08T16:18:02+00:00">
                 March 8, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/alexpearlman/">
                 Alex Pearlman
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-resigns-twitter-reactions/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p style="text-align: left;">
              Citing wanting to spend more time with his family, Food and Drug Administration commissioner
              <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/03/05/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-who-raised-alarms-about-teen-vaping-resigns/?utm_term=.08551763353e">
               Scott Gottlieb announced his resignation this week
              </a>
              . Broadly liked on both sides of the aisle and
              <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/06/biotech-stocks-fall-after-fda-chief-scott-gottlieb-resigns.html">
               within the biopharma industry
              </a>
              , Gottlieb, a former physician and cancer survivor, made teen tobacco use a major issue during his two-year tenure.
             </p>
             <p>
              In addition to working on lowering drug prices and bringing generic drugs to the market faster,
              <a href="https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/432708-fda-chief-scott-gottlieb-resigns-reports">
               both priorities for the Trump administration
              </a>
              , Gottlieb has been a fierce advocate for
              <a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/03/05/gottlieb-fda-milestones-1242394">
               a number of other public health issues
              </a>
              , focusing the FDA’s attention on combating the opioid epidemic, creating harsher regulations for dietary supplements, and even
              <a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/03/05/gottlieb-fda-milestones-1242394">
               “preserving Michelle Obama’s sugars labeling.”
              </a>
             </p>
             <p>
              Gottlieb had previously worked as a
              <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/05/health/scott-gottlieb-resigns-fda.html">
               venture capitalist and board member for pharmaceutical companies,
              </a>
              and made millions from his work in that industry, which caused alarm on the left when his appointment was originally announced. However, the commissioner surprised critics by divesting his interest in drug companies and calling for stronger and updated regulations across health-related industries.
             </p>
             <p>
              Given his penchant for being chatty on Twitter, we rounded up some of the reactions to Gottlieb’s resignation from Bill of Health’s friends and family.
             </p>
             <p>
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/fda-commissioner-gottlieb-resigns-twitter-reactions/#more-27338">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
