          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/the-nhs-complaints-system-wither-the-toxic-cocktail-image/" title="The NHS Complaints System: Wither the Toxic Cocktail Image?">
            <img alt="UCL A&amp;E entrance" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="25777" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"4","credit":"Getty Images\/iStockphoto","camera":"NIKON D7000","caption":"Pedestrian entrance to the Accident and Emergency Unit at University College Hospital as viewed from the pavement on the Euston Road.","created_timestamp":"1440873838","copyright":"Amanda Lewis","focal_length":"26","iso":"160","shutter_speed":"0.003125","title":"Accident and Emergency Entrance","orientation":"1"}' data-image-title="Accident and Emergency Entrance" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?fit=648%2C429" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?fit=300%2C199" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?fit=2128%2C1409" data-orig-size="2128,1409" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/accident-and-emergency-entrance/" height="410" src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/ThinkstockPhotos-487317170.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/the-nhs-complaints-system-wither-the-toxic-cocktail-image/" rel="bookmark">
               The NHS Complaints System: Wither the Toxic Cocktail Image?
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/the-nhs-complaints-system-wither-the-toxic-cocktail-image/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-07T10:59:58+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-07T10:59:58+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/jtingle/">
                 John Tingle
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/the-nhs-complaints-system-wither-the-toxic-cocktail-image/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              The National Health Service in England has been trying for many years to get its complaints system right, but it has never succeeded. A great number of reports have been published on the system over the years, some dating back for at least a quarter of a century.
             </p>
             <p>
              The
              <a href="https://cqc.org.uk/">
               Care Quality Commission
              </a>
              (CQC ) the independent regulator of health and social care in England have just published a
              <a href="https://www.cqc.org.uk/news/releases/new-research-cqc-shows-people-regret-not-raising-concerns-about-their-care-–-those-who">
               report
              </a>
              launching a “Declare Your Care” campaign, which raises several important issues about the
              <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/using-the-nhs/about-the-nhs/how-to-complain-to-the-nhs/">
               NHS complaints system
              </a>
              .
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/the-nhs-complaints-system-wither-the-toxic-cocktail-image/#more-27301">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27304 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-animal-research category-crispr category-environment category-genetics category-global-health-2 category-gmo-food category-health-law-policy category-malaria category-public-health category-student-fellows tag-crispr tag-ethics tag-gene-drives tag-health-law tag-history-of-malaria-in-the-us tag-malaria" id="post-27304">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/" title="Malaria Eradication: For Africa as America">
            <img alt="Close up of a mosquito sucking blood on human skin. This mosquito is a carrier of Malaria, Encephalitis, Dengue and Zika virus." class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27336" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"0"}' data-image-title="shutterstock_628503122" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?fit=648%2C433" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?fit=2000%2C1335" data-orig-size="2000,1335" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/shutterstock_628503122/" height="410" src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_628503122.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/" rel="bookmark">
               Malaria Eradication: For Africa as America
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-07T10:30:36+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-07T10:30:36+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/jtoomey/">
                 James Toomey
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              There is a page in the history books waiting to be written for the eradication of malaria. In recent years, malaria has killed more people globally than
              <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/war-and-peace">
               war
              </a>
              —it’s killed predominately
              <a href="https://www.unicef.org/health/files/health_africamalaria.pdf">
               children
              </a>
              , and predominately in
              <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/malaria">
               sub-Saharan Africa
              </a>
              . Despite being
              <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/malaria/about/disease.html">
               curable
              </a>
              , and
              <a href="https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/205565/WHO_HTM_GMP_2016.3_eng.pdf;jsessionid=50670AB9B9C68F6F5CF02549447BF866?sequence=1">
               eliminated
              </a>
              from most developed countries, malaria is the
              <a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2014/09/16/347727459/which-contagious-diseases-are-the-deadliest">
               fifth deadliest
              </a>
              infectious disease in the world.
             </p>
             <p>
              A
              <a href="http://www.ruthmueller.info/members/">
               team of scientists in Italy
              </a>
              is looking to write that history.
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/07/malaria-eradication-for-africa-as-america/#more-27304">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27329 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-hivaids category-public-health category-student-fellows" id="post-27329">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/" title="HIV Treatment: Functional Cures are Just One Aspect of Newsworthy Progress">
            <img alt="3D illustration of anatomically correct HIV Virus floating in the bloodstream" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27331" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="&lt;p&gt;3D illustration of anatomically correct HIV Virus floating in the bloodstream&lt;/p&gt;
" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"0"}' data-image-title="shutterstock_446279956" data-large-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?fit=648%2C433" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w" data-medium-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-orig-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?fit=2000%2C1335" data-orig-size="2000,1335" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/shutterstock_446279956/" height="410" src="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/shutterstock_446279956.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/" rel="bookmark">
               HIV Treatment: Functional Cures are Just One Aspect of Newsworthy Progress
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-06T09:53:38+00:00">
                 March 6, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-06T16:02:54+00:00">
                 March 6, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/msatta/">
                 Mark Satta
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              Major news networks around the globe this week broke the story that a second HIV-positive patient appears to have been
              <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/05/london-hiv-patient-becomes-worlds-second-aids-cure-hope.html">
               “functionally cured” of HIV
              </a>
              .
             </p>
             <p>
              In a welcome piece of good news, the world learned that an anonymous individual, known simply as “the London patient” has experienced a year and a half of
              <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/04/health/hiv-remission-london-patient-study-bn/index.html">
               sustained remission
              </a>
              of the HIV virus without medication. The patient entered into remission after receiving a bone marrow transplant from someone naturally resistant to HIV infection. This is the second functional cure of HIV of its kind. The first such case
              <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4287108/">
               occurred in 2007
              </a>
              .
             </p>
             <p>
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/06/hiv-treatment-functional-cures-are-just-one-aspect-of-newsworthy-progress/#more-27329">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27306 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-announcements category-events" id="post-27306">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/" title="Jennifer Prah Ruger: The World Needs a New Global Health Architecture">
            <img alt="World map where continents are in blue pixels" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27307" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"0"}' data-image-title="Global Health Justice &amp; Governance – EMAIL" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?fit=648%2C358" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?resize=300%2C165 300w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?zoom=3&amp;resize=750%2C410 2250w" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?fit=300%2C165" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?fit=2687%2C1482" data-orig-size="2687,1482" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/global-health-justice-governance-email/" height="410" src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Global-Health-Justice-Governance-EMAIL.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/" rel="bookmark">
               Jennifer Prah Ruger: The World Needs a New Global Health Architecture
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-05T10:57:22+00:00">
                 March 5, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-02-28T14:29:59+00:00">
                 February 28, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/petrieflom/">
                 The Petrie-Flom Center Staff
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              In a world beset by serious and unconscionable health disparities, by dangerous contagions that can circle our globalized planet in hours, and by a bewildering confusion of health actors and systems, humankind needs a new vision, a new architecture, new coordination among renewed systems to ensure central health capabilities for all. In her new book, “
              <a href="https://global.oup.com/academic/product/global-health-justice-and-governance-9780199694631?cc=us&amp;lang=en&amp;">
               Global Health Justice and Governance
              </a>
              <em>
               ,”
              </em>
              Dr. Prah Ruger lays out the critical problems facing the world today and offers a new theory of justice and governance as a way to resolve these seemingly intractable issues.
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/05/jennifer-prah-ruger-the-world-needs-a-new-global-health-architecture/#more-27306">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27280 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-health-law-policy category-medical-quality category-mental-health category-public-health category-rebecca-friedman category-social-determinants-of-health category-student-fellows tag-maternal-health" id="post-27280">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/report-maternal-mental-health-must-be-a-top-priority/" title="Report: Maternal Mental Health Must be a Top Priority">
            <img alt="" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="26845" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"0"}' data-image-title="baby_lap_neonatal_mother" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?fit=648%2C432" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w, https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?zoom=3&amp;resize=750%2C410 2250w" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?fit=2500%2C1667" data-orig-size="2500,1667" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/symposia/how-patients-are-creating-the-future-of-medicine/baby_lap_neonatal_mother/" height="410" src="https://i2.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/baby_lap_neonatal_mother-e1551450827127.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/report-maternal-mental-health-must-be-a-top-priority/" rel="bookmark">
               Report: Maternal Mental Health Must be a Top Priority
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/report-maternal-mental-health-must-be-a-top-priority/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-03-01T09:34:00+00:00">
                 March 1, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-07T10:34:04+00:00">
                 March 7, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/rfriedman/">
                 Rebecca Friedman
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/report-maternal-mental-health-must-be-a-top-priority/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              The
              <a href="https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/">
               U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF)
              </a>
              , published recommendations recently
              <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2724195?alert=article">
               urging clinicians to refer pregnant and postpartum women to counseling
              </a>
              if they are at risk of depression.
             </p>
             <p>
              <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2724195?alert=article">
               The recommendations
              </a>
              respond to the prevalence of perinatal depression, which is
              <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/12/health/maternal-depression-prevention-pregnancy-.html">
               considered to be the most common pregnancy complication
              </a>
              . Perinatal depression,
              <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/12/health/maternal-depression-prevention-pregnancy-.html">
               affects up to one in seven women
              </a>
              and can
              <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3083253/">
               develop at any time after a woman becomes pregnant,
              </a>
              immediately following the brith of a child, or even up to a year after.
             </p>
             <p>
              Among the many concerning potential consequences of maternal depression are premature births and low birth weights, as well as neglect and inattentiveness from mothers after the baby is born, which can subject infants to risk of additional problems, according to
              <a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/02/12/693868871/task-force-to-prevent-postpartum-depression-at-risk-women-should-get-counseling">
               Karina Davidson, a USPSTF member who helped write the recent recommendations
              </a>
              .
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/report-maternal-mental-health-must-be-a-top-priority/#more-27280">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
