            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              For over two decades, Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law, in conjunction with the IU School of Medicine, has conferred the
              <a href="https://mckinneylaw.iu.edu/health-law/mmk/index.html">
               McDonald-Merrill-Ketcham Memorial Award for Excellence in Law and Medicine
              </a>
              .
             </p>
             <p>
              This year’s honoree was Dr.
              <a href="https://dellmed.utexas.edu/directory/karen-desalvo">
               Karen DeSalvo
              </a>
              , who is currently Professor of Medicine and Population Health at the University of Texas at Austin Dell Medical School.
              <span class="Apple-converted-space">
              </span>
              She served in the Obama Administration as National Coordinator for Health Information Technology, and Acting Assistant Secretary for Health, and previously was the Health Commissioner for the City of New Orleans.
             </p>
             <p>
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/03/01/karen-desalvo-on-the-week-in-health-law-podcast/#more-27313">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27321 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-health-law-policy" id="post-27321">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/" title="Trauma at the Border: Can Neuroscience Inform Legal Advocacy?">
            <img alt="Black and white image of children playing in the fence at the US-Mexico border." class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27322" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"7.1","credit":"","camera":"NIKON D3000","caption":"","created_timestamp":"1350142716","copyright":"","focal_length":"20","iso":"100","shutter_speed":"0.005","title":"","orientation":"1"}' data-image-title="La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia Commons_CC-BY-SA 4.0" data-large-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?fit=648%2C435" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w, https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?zoom=3&amp;resize=750%2C410 2250w" data-medium-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?fit=300%2C201" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?fit=2896%2C1944" data-orig-size="2896,1944" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/la_border_protoplasmakid_wikimedia-commons_cc-by-sa-4-0/" height="410" src="https://i1.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/La_Border_ProtoplasmaKid_Wikimedia-Commons_CC-BY-SA-4.0.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/" rel="bookmark">
               Trauma at the Border: Can Neuroscience Inform Legal Advocacy?
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-02-28T12:47:38+00:00">
                 February 28, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-02-28T14:29:03+00:00">
                 February 28, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/fxshen/">
                 Francis X. Shen
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              This week the House Judiciary Committee
              <a href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/26/scott-lloyd-migrant-family-separations-1216323">
               begins its formal inquiries
              </a>
              into the Trump Administration’s separation of children from their families as part of a “zero tolerance” immigration policy in 2018.
             </p>
             <p>
              The policy of family separation was curtailed after public outcry, but the trauma remains. Experts in developmental neuroscience have explained that the trauma of separation has likely
              <a href="https://www.brookings.edu/blog/future-development/2018/07/09/the-enormous-cost-of-toxic-stress-repairing-damage-to-refugee-and-separated-children/">
               produced long-term toxic effects
              </a>
              on the brains of these young people.
             </p>
             <p>
              Moreover, the trauma of separation is only one of many stressors affecting the lives of those seeking refuge and asylum. Children who witness intense violence and flee war-ravaged lands are at
              <a href="https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/06/refugee-mental-health-trauma-children-lesbos-greece-crisis-world-refugee-day-culture/">
               greater risk of psychological harm
              </a>
              . Children at the U.S. border encounter even more trauma when they enter an immigration system where the Supreme Court has recently held that they can be
              <a href="https://www.npr.org/2018/02/27/589096901/supreme-court-ruling-means-immigrants-can-continue-to-be-detained-indefinitely">
               detained indefinitely
              </a>
              .
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/28/how-can-neuroscience-and-the-law-address-trauma-at-the-border/#more-27321">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
         <!-- #post-## -->
         <article class="post-27316 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-bioethics category-biotechnology category-crispr category-events category-genetics category-health-law-policy category-intellectual-property category-reproductive-technology tag-crispr tag-crispr-babies tag-gene-editing tag-genome-editing tag-george-chuch tag-harvard-medical-school tag-portal" id="post-27316">
          <div class="blog-item-wrap">
           <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/" title="Gene Editing and Intellectual Property: A Useful Mix?">
            <img alt="Abstract representation of DNA double helix" class="single-featured wp-post-image jetpack-lazy-image" data-attachment-id="27320" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-description="" data-image-meta='{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":"","orientation":"0"}' data-image-title="shutterstock_780211078" data-large-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?fit=648%2C433" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px" data-lazy-src="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?resize=750%2C410&amp;is-pending-load=1" data-lazy-srcset="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?resize=750%2C410 750w, https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?resize=1140%2C624 1140w, https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?zoom=2&amp;resize=750%2C410 1500w" data-medium-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-orig-file="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?fit=2000%2C1335" data-orig-size="2000,1335" data-permalink="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/shutterstock_780211078/" height="410" src="https://i0.wp.com/blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/shutterstock_780211078.jpg?resize=750%2C410" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" width="750"/>
           </a>
           <div class="post-inner-content">
            <header class="entry-header page-header">
             <h2 class="entry-title">
              <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/" rel="bookmark">
               Gene Editing and Intellectual Property: A Useful Mix?
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="entry-meta">
              <span class="posted-on">
               <i class="fa fa-calendar-alt">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/" rel="bookmark">
                <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-02-27T11:43:36+00:00">
                 February 27, 2019
                </time>
                <time class="updated" datetime="2019-03-08T16:17:15+00:00">
                 March 8, 2019
                </time>
               </a>
              </span>
              <span class="byline">
               <i class="fa fa-user">
               </i>
               <span class="author vcard">
                <a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/author/jsherkow/">
                 Jacob S. Sherkow
                </a>
               </span>
              </span>
              <span class="comments-link">
               <i class="fa fa-comments">
               </i>
               <a href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/#respond">
                Leave a comment
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
             <!-- .entry-meta -->
            </header>
            <!-- .entry-header -->
            <div class="entry-content">
             <p>
              <a href="https://heller.brandeis.edu/facguide/person.html?emplid=fed1af017db070b94ce59c13714f1e7970a787ad" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
               <strong>
                ​
               </strong>
              </a>
              <em>
               The
               <a href="http://bioethics.hms.harvard.edu/health-policy-and-bioethics-consortia" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                Health Policy and Bioethics Consortia
               </a>
               is a monthly series that convenes two international experts from different fields or vantage points to discuss how biomedical innovation and health care delivery are affected by various ethical norms, laws, and regulations.
              </em>
             </p>
             <p>
              <em>
               They are organized by the Harvard Medical School
               <a href="http://bioethics.hms.harvard.edu/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                Center for Bioethics
               </a>
               and the
               <a href="https://www.portalresearch.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                Program on Regulation, Therapeutics, and Law (PORTAL)
               </a>
               at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, in collaboration with the
               <a href="http://petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                Petrie-Flom Center for Health Law Policy, Biotechnology, and Bioethics
               </a>
               at Harvard Law School. Support provided by the Oswald DeN. Cammann Fund at Harvard University.
              </em>
             </p>
             <p>
              <em>
               A light lunch will be provided. This event is free and open to the public, but space is limited and registration is required. Please note that attendees will need to show ID in order to enter the venue.
               <a href="https://events.r20.constantcontact.com/register/eventReg?oeidk=a07eg3st12q9bafdee4&amp;oseq=&amp;c=09ac8b90-5c9a-11e5-b1d8-d4ae529cddd3&amp;ch=0a216d70-5c9a-11e5-b280-d4ae529cddd3" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                Register now!
               </a>
              </em>
             </p>
             <p>
             </p>
             <p>
              One way of thinking about genome editing is through the lens of the legal and ethical obligations of ensuring the technology is deployed safely and accurately, for the betterment of human society.
             </p>
             <p>
              Or, if that’s a mouthful for you, genome editing’s
              <em>
               rights
              </em>
              —and
              <em>
               wrongs
              </em>
              . Which brings me to a talk I’ll* be giving at Harvard Medical School on March 8:
              <a href="http://bioethics.hms.harvard.edu/upcoming-events?trumbaEmbed=eventid%3D129494473%26view%3Devent%26-childview%3D">
               “Genome Editing: Rights and Wrongs”
              </a>
              I feel obligated, however, to asterisk the personal pronoun (“I”) because, in truth, what I’ll be doing is sharing the stage with one the world’s most celebrated scientists,
              <a href="http://arep.med.harvard.edu/gmc/">
               George Church
              </a>
              , world-renowned bioethicist,
              <a href="http://bioethics.hms.harvard.edu/person/faculty-members/jeantine-lunshof">
               Jeantine Lunshof
              </a>
              , and moderated by health policy guru,
              <a href="http://bioethics.hms.harvard.edu/person/faculty-members/aaron-kesselheim">
               Aaron Kesselheim
              </a>
              .
              <a class="more-link" href="http://blog.petrieflom.law.harvard.edu/2019/02/27/gene-editing-and-intellectual-property-a-useful-mix/#more-27316">
               Read More
              </a>
             </p>
            </div>
            <!-- .entry-content -->
           </div>
          </div>
         </article>
